Research the state of the art in code clone detection algorithms, covering all four clone types. Type 1 clones are exact textual copies. Type 2 clones have identical structure but renamed identifiers. Type 3 clones have similar structure with added, removed, or modified statements. Type 4 clones are semantically equivalent but syntactically different. For each type, document the dominant algorithmic approach: for Type 1 and 2, compare line-hashing approaches like CP-Miner versus token-based approaches like CCFinder and CCFinderX. For Type 3, compare suffix tree methods, PDG-based techniques like Deckard, and the NiCad approach using flexible pretty-printing plus LCS diff. For Type 4, document the semantic clone detection research using program dependence graphs and machine learning embedding approaches. Also research SourcererCC and its scalability approach using token overlap and inverted indexes. Document the precision and recall benchmarks each tool achieves on the BigCloneBench dataset. Include information on the minimum clone size thresholds commonly used (in lines or tokens) and how they affect false positive rates. The goal is to inform the design of a production clone detector that must run in under 60 seconds on 50,000 lines of code and support Python, JavaScript, TypeScript, Java, Go, and Rust.
